\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
null hypothesis
\series default
, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

, is usually the nullification of a claim.
 Unless evidence from the data indicates otherwise, the null hypothesis
 is assumed to be true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
alternate hypothesis
\series default
, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or sometimes denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{a}$
\end_inset

), is customarily the claim itself.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The
\series bold
 test statistic
\series default
, denoted by TS, is a function of the sample measurements upon which the
 statistical decision will be based.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
rejection region
\series default
 (or a 
\emph on
critical region
\emph default
) is the region that specifies the values of the observed test statistic
 for which the null hypothesis will be rejected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Conclusion
\series default
: Reject or fail to reject the null hypothesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Interpret the results
\series default
: State in words what the conclusion means to the problem we started with.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
