\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Real differences between the point estimate and null value are easier to
 detect with larger samples.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However, very large samples will result in
\series bold
 statistical significance
\series default
 even for tiny differences between the sample mean and the null value, even
 when the difference is not
\series bold
 practically significant
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is especially important to research: if we conduct a study, we want
 to focus on finding meaningful results–
\emph on
effect size
\emph default
 (we want observed differences to be 
\emph on
real
\emph default
, but also large enough 
\emph on
to matter
\emph default
).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This inability for the statistical machinery to distinguish between the
 two types of significance is sometimes called 
\emph on
Lindley’s paradox
\emph default
: With enough data, you’ll reject any hypothesis at all!
\end_layout

\end_deeper
